76561198048974498,Recommended,250620,10288133,"Posted: 30 May, 2014",all,rjmacready,"I'm going to review this one a tad prematurely; that is to say, in spite of having only played what I believe constitutes about the first two-thirds of the game (as this is the third recently-released horror game or DLC I've bought which my three year-old, piece-of♥♥♥♥♥♥laptop seemingly can't handle, technologically-speaking...thankfully, a new computer is on the horizon).I feel pretty confident in opining, however, that if you like the sound of the game's basic premise - in short, Amnesia-style horror from the perspective of a two-year old toddler - this isn't liable to disappoint. Unless you're one of the ""this game it too short"" brigade, in which case you probably should have learned by now not to buy these kinda games, especially at full-price.It's slow to build, and a LOOOOONG time before you encounter any true ""danger"" within the game. But when that moment comes in which you realise that, yes, the spooky creatures you've been safely spotting from afar ARE actually interested in moving in for a closer look, it's every bit as legitimately pants-browning as the best horror games you've ever played.What's more, the ""child-like"" perspective, while not fully reinventing the wheel, does put quite a different spin on well-worn first-person adventure gaming themes. For example, where other games would require your character to push a crate up against a wall in order to access a high vent, in this one your toddler has to pull a kitchen chair up just to reach a regular-height surburban door handle! Everything feels quite dauntingly HUGE to our diminutive hero, making it feel not unlike Alice trapped in a nightmare Wonderland (one in which she never managed to find the antidote to the shrinking potion)!It's super-spooky, super-imaginative, has amazingly atmospheric sound design, and your best friend/sole ally is a talking teddy-bear! So what are you waiting for? Unless the answer is ""a better computer"", you really don't have an excuse...unless you're a complete wuss, of course. C'mon, are you really so much of a wuss that you're not willing to brave the same horrors as a TWO YEAR-OLD KID?! Teddy's waiting for you...Verdict: 9/10."
