76561198021603745,Recommended,250620,31727557,Posted: 13 May,all,Zatarrax,"Not really scary (apart from some boots and rain coats), but the main idea makes it worth it: After so many years it is just fun to be a toddler again!P.S.: Don't forget to play the extra prologue after you finished the main game by going to Chapter Selection."
,Recommended,250620,21376947,"Posted: 21 February, 2016",all,EthanCrambo,"This review contains a couple of mere spoilers.Among the Sleep has a very impressive affect on the player. It shows the great idea that only a genius could think of - using the perspective of a baby. Throughout this baby perspective, we can clearly notice that the baby has worries over many things like their mother's scream. At the beginning of the game, the character's mother goes to answer the door that had just had the doorbell ring. The mother then screams which queues the music and visual effects to give a dramatic effect. This happens to show that the baby feels stressed and panicked as though the mother is giving a distress call - an in-danger tone. I find this is a very creative idea and the creator really understands how emotion is built up in a game.After seeing the monster, I have a slight lust of disappointment, for as soon as a monster is shown in a game, that ruins the horror element of a build up. No studios are able to create a monster that is more horrifying that what we, as consumers, create in our head from mysterious build-ups, such as lighting effects and creaky floorboards. As soon as a monster is shown in a game, it automatically drops some tension and makes the player less scared of the monster. This game has lost the horrific momentum by showing the monster, and the monster doesn't look very scary, but I guess there are limits as to how scary you can make a monster look. And to be quite straight... what is a monster? A monster is a horrific creature or person that is created IN OUT HEADS by dramatic effects and noises. Making a monster be shown in a game really doesn't make it a monster anymore.The teddy bear's voice acting and sounds are very good. The sound effects successfully create tension and the teddy bear successfully sounds like aPaedophile- I mean a nice friend.  In addition, the animations of movement in the game are very smooth, however are a little slow and... the opposite of slick. Whatever that word is.As far as I can judge on the game mechanics, they are quite simple and not all that amazing. Animations for the things the character uses are very simple and could be improved through more time in development.I do believe this game has a really good story line, really good twists and successfully shows the in-depth perspective of a baby in every-day situations. Among the Sleep shows a definite prime example of what a baby would think about as they go to sleep on a dark, windy night. It shows how the baby is petrified and shows how simple things are over-exaggerated in the baby's mind, such as a wardrobe.Overall, I think this game really is worth the play and if you don't play this game, you'd be missing out on a lot of interesting perspective."
,Recommended,250620,20262661,"Posted: 3 January, 2016",all,Trickling Trisha,"A fresh view on horror.I remember being intruiged when I heard about the planned release of Among the Sleep, since it looked like a breath of fresh air in the horror genre. I am very pleased to say that I was not disappointed when I finally got round to playing it.What you can expect is an immersive atmosphere, a lovable Teddy and a generally pleasant experience. This isn't another over-the-top gore and jumpscare mashup, but a carefully crafted horror experience which plays out from the perspective of a toddler. Not something you see everyday.I played through the entire game in one night with my girlfriend, who, although not a fan of horror games, agreed that the game was well polished and enjoyable, with a balance of scariness and respite.I highly recommend this to people who are looking for a gateway to the horror genre, not wanting to throw themselves into deep water, but who want to start their dark adventure. ;)"
