76561198069735211,Recommended,250620,31213309,Posted: 17 April,all,DaHotFuzz,"I loved the concept of Among the Sleep.  How many games have you play through the eyes of a toddler? This is certainly the only one I am aware of.  I can give bonus points for originality here and in a horror title no less, which is no easy thing to do these days.Among the Sleep does a terrific job at immersing you into the world because of its engrossing atmosphere and ambiance. I will admit I was pretty spooked at certain points.  The mechanics are reminiscent of Frictional Games' Amnesia and Penumbra titles; you can interact with items in the world but there is zero puzzle solving that you will find in the aforementioned games.  It is more so a matter of finding and interacting with objects that help you progress through the game.You cannot fight the few enemies encountered, instead, you must avoid them at all costs and make your way past them.  This characteristic of horror games I have found is either absolutely loved or hated typically.  I personally enjoy it because it puts the player in a helpless state and gives you all the more reason to be scared.  This is, after all, the effect all horror games should invoke.  But there are those who are annoyed or frustrated by this and I can understand that.Among the Sleep unfortunately suffers from a few issues however.  My biggest problem with it is the technical issues I have experienced.  The amount of stuttering I encountered was surprisingly bothersome.  Considering the very short length of the game (anywhere between 1 and 4 hours depending on your playstyle and if you are hunting for achievements), you would have expected it to be significantly more polished.  The stuttering and major fps drops are distracting and certainly take away from game's immersion.  I could have 150 fps for a moment then suddenly it drops just below 60 and it is awfully noticeable.  My rig also is running on an 6600k, gtx 980, and 16 gb of ram, way above the game's recommended requirements.The last but smaller problem I had with the game is the save system.  Throughout each chapter, as you play, the game will notify you that it's saving which is all well and good if you die because you will restart from your last save point.  Unfortunately though, if you quit a chapter mid game, you will have to start that chapter from the very beginning.  Not a huge deal given its short length but misleading because when you see the game autosaving, you assume you can just quit and return at the moment of the auto save, not the case here.All this aside, Among the Sleep is a unique experience and is definitely worth adding to your library.  I would suggest waiting for a nice sale to pick it up though."
,Recommended,250620,10284710,"Posted: 30 May, 2014",all,Goblin King Jareth,"When I was very young and prone to getting seperated from my parents in department stores I would later have nightmares about hiding in the center of the circular clothing racks, peeking out from under heavy wool coats and suits while monsters sought my tender flesh in the darkness.This is just one of the intense emotional experiences of this game which is painted from every spectrum of emotional palette you can imagine: from the rainbow joy of discovery and exploration as you search for your mother to the black depths of terror and loneliness.This game is not only a masterpiece of survival horror but a poignant piece of storytelling at the same time.  It terrifies on a completely psychological level with a perfect counterpoint of harmonious safety and aesthetically amazing exploration as you get closer to your mother and the end of the tale.This is one of the most intense five hours I've ever spent on a game title and everyone should experience this game no matter what genre of games you are into."
,Recommended,250620,10286834,"Posted: 30 May, 2014",all,ByteØ,"There is nothing scarier than being a toddler who's looking for their mum, while crawling through creepy environments that have something wicked lurking in every shadow.It is not often that I find a horror game worthy to be standing tall beside great titles such as Amnesia and Slender, but Among the Sleep is definitely one of those horror games. While the game clearly reveals its Indie roots by having a playtime value of about two hours, depending on how much of a scaredy cat you are, it's dripping with a great concoction of creepy visuals, haunting sounds and eerie music. It has done what many so called horror titles of this day and age fail to do; frighten me. Among the Sleep shines in making you feel like the fragile little child you control, and it's just enough to make your skin crawl as you struggle to open doors and find elaborate ways to climb on top of a drawer.Check it out when you've got the time and cash! This game is definitely worth your time if you're a fan of horror that has the potential to make you soil your pants."
