,Recommended,250620,17279888,"Posted: 29 July, 2015",all,The Sexiest Vixen Ever,"Holy ♥♥♥♥ing♥♥♥♥♥♥balls. And all of that first sentence is stars immediately. This game is absolutely incredible. If only sheerly for the perspective not only in gameplay, but in narration...Just like the more well known FNAF, there's a lot of stuff hiding in plain sight that reveals some history and the going ons that lead to what's happening right now. Although this time you're not a security guard and they aren't animatronics. You're a very very young toddler of 2, and your life is depicted in drawings. Crude ones, as you'd suspect. As you make your way through hell and back you get tidbits of information that lead suspicions to reality. Soon enough, you live that reality.Some say the imagination of a child is the strongest. Perhaps that is true, as is depicted in this game. What is real and what isn't real doesn't matter any more. You're 2. The world is a big scary place and you're... You, in comparison. Tiny. Dfenseless. Horrified.I found my self mesmerized, comforted, calmed... Then was thrust head first into hell. With incredibly atmospheric gameplay and stunning music this game had me balls deep before the ♥♥♥♥ing tutorial ended. Sucking me in quicker than a whirl pool. Before I knew it the world was like I said, big, terrifying... And I'm all alone... Well, not entirely. Teddy comes  along to aid you but ultimately does nothing other than exposition and plot driving through the stuff that can't be explained so well with out actually telling the player.Teddy tags along and acts mainly as your flashlight. And my god was it comforting to have some ♥♥♥♥ing light. Keep the gama down, play in the dark, keep the sound a little high.It can be rather hard to see and actually explore with the gama too low and too high it ruins the experience. Finding the right balance of both lighting and sound is a bit tricky at first but once done the game is that much more amazing.Its a bit hard to find places to hide when you can't see though, and you can't use Teddy's flashlight ability when crawling and you can't run when using him. You have to stand and meander, which makes it even more stressful when running from the pants fillingly terrifying monsters chasing you. Don't forget, this game is incredibly immersive. If you get immersed, you'd be filling your pants too.The game is a cocktail of smooth relaxing and haunting moments of serenity while momma hums for you, or a music box alludes to peace. Then you get to a puzzle. The puzzles in this game are exceptionally well done as they force the player to explore places they may not have explored. Although it can cause backtracking and a bit of confusion. The game looks, sounds, and feels great though so meandering through the dark, in the dark, scared out of your mind can't be all that bad. After, and sometimes durring, puzzles there's sections of horror. Your little tiny baby legs take you in and out of the gates of hell over and over as the nightmares of the real world /are/ your real world. Constantly being stalked by gargantuant shadowy beings that are seemingly always 3 steps behind you. Always on your heels. Always around the corner.The screen gets a weird loopy filter and its Amnesia all over again. ""Runrunrunrunrun! OOOH FUUUUH-UUCK!"" Sometimes escaping is easy, sometimes not so much as you bump your baby head into the upper part of a hidey hole and get eaten by a hellish nightmare.If you liked Amnesia but want something a little different, this is the game for you. Had a ♥♥♥♥♥♥ childhood? Want to relive the terror of said childhood? This is the game for you. New to horror? Want to try horror? This is the game for you. Want a cream pie on the outside, but on the inside its the heart of Chtulu? This is the game for you.Pros: Stunning atmospheric gameplay elements and music creating instant immersion. Simple control scheme that's easy to get used to. Pulse pounding horror as you run for your godamn life. Kinda casual. Best when played alone in your room with all the lights off. And no wall pressed against your back... Don't worry, daddy's comin'. Just don't look over your shoulder.Cons: Climbing and general mantling is a bit wonk and a bit hard to get used to. Perfect lighting is hard to balance because some areas are just so damn dark, which makes hiding a little tedious at times. Maybe a little too forgiving as each death starts you 15 feet from where you died with all of your previous inputs, that means everything- including enviornmental changes, still in play. Some puzzles are a little too ambiguous with what they want out of you. The answer is sitting right in front of your face, but that's the problem. Its sometimes a little too obvious. Sometimes a little too hidden.Either way it was an absolutely incredible game. If you have the money laying around I would suggest picking it up and giving it a go. If you have headphones you're in for a treat. Definitely one of my best, if second or third, horror experiences."
