76561198096079278,Recommended,250620,16529705,"Posted: 19 June, 2015",all,FriendFive,"I really like this game a lot--it's short, sad, and sweet. What makes it unique is the perspective; it's a first person perspective horror game where you play as a 2-year-old toddler. The game really makes you see the world through the imagination and fears of a little child. The visual design of the game succeeds in making benign everyday objects look menacing when in the dark. Is that some sort of monster standing there watching you? Or is it simply a coat on a coat rack with some boots sticking out the bottom of it? Even your own toys can sometimes seem unsettling. I liked how, whenever you see written text in the game, like in an open book, for example, it looks like gibberish, since your character can't read. Sound effects are used effectively at the right times to evoke a sense of dread and fear.In my opinion, the star of the show here is Teddy, your imaginary friend teddy bear who seems alive and who is with you you traverse the dark, avoiding a monster and looking for your missing mother. Teddy is an ambiguous character; cute n' creepy. Is he there to help you or is he not to be trusted? He is well voice-acted, but there are long sections of the game where you almost forget he is with you because he doesn't have much to say. I realize this is under the pretense that you both have to be quite so as not to alert the monster to your presence, but I just feel like Teddy could have been used more in some of the middle sections of the game.I'm not going lie, this game can really get you into the mindset of a small child and I did find myself weeping after the climax and at the end. The game can be scary, but there's no blood and guts or anything. But be aware that the game delves into issues that kids shouldn't have to face, but sometimes do. The evidence to me that this game successfully told a story with some emotional impact was the fact that it gave me the feels even though I had a pretty stable and happy childhood."
76561197984132084,Recommended,250620,10305583,"Posted: 31 May, 2014",all,TheShadowCookie,"Are you searching for a rather unique type of horror experience? Has your thirst for psychological torment this year not been quenched yet? Do you crave to relive old childhood nightmares? Then Among The Sleep might be for you...This delightfully terrifying experience grants gamers the opportunity to explore a creepy Silent Hill-esque world of terror through the eyes of a toddler. That premise alone should capture anyone's curiosity. For what does a helpless baby represent the most? Exactly... Helplessness. You are no soldier, no athletic investigator - just a baby in the land of giants. One that can barely walk on two feet. You don't get to see that type of scenario every day. But what can be said about the game itself?Both music and sounds, arguably the most important parts of any horror game, do not disappoint. You'll often be looking over your shoulder to check whether that ominous noise in the distance was really just part of the ambiance or instead a sinister monster stalking you. Among The Sleep definitely plays it's cards well, and spends a good quarter of it's length on excellent build-up to the main events. Especially the first big area, a forested house located within a foggy swamp, managed to freak me out again and again. I'd not want to return there anytime soon, that's for sure.In terms of gameplay you'll be collecting stuff in order to access new places. A lot of stuff. Perhaps too much stuff? Eh, it didn't bother me in all honesty. The environments are beautifully designed, and keep things interesting enough to overshadow the simplistic puzzles. I swear to god though... That evil forest. Or the playground before it. The atmosphere oozes greatness around every corner. You'll never know what to expect next. Better grow used to being all alone, for your only ""companion"" happens to be a teddy bear - one who also serves as a sort of light source if hugged tightly. How charming. Well, you take what you can get as a toddler. Flashlights ain't cheap!HOWEVER... Among The Sleep unfortunately isn't perfect. The second half of it, in my opinion, happens to be much weaker than the first, which feels as if the developers spent most of their budget on it, only to run out of significant ideas later on. This is quite a shame indeed. And it doesn't stop there. The game is also a rather short experience. Two - three hours, maybe four if you take it slow, are what most players will probably get out of it. And that length is somewhat disappointing, considering that you need to pay 20 bucks for it. Even the story, despite feeling intriguing at points, ultimately fails to outweigh these negatives. After reaching the end, you'll be left with that bothersome ""is it over already?"" feeling in your gut. Such wasted potential.In conclusion, I'd say that you should give Among The Sleep a try. I greatly enjoyed my time with it, despite some flaws along the way. And chances are you will as well. But it might be wise to wait for a price drop. Chances are you'd probably feel a little cheated to pay 20 bucks for a game that only last two hours if you play through it in a fast-paced manner.TL;DR: Good horror. Starts out strong, leaves a little to be desired in the second half. Overall too short for 20 bucks.FINAL VERDICT: 7 / 10"
