,Not Recommended,250620,32189589,Posted: 4 June,all,Fugue,"This is a tough one to put into the binary of ""yes/no"" recommendations. It is put together really well. The challenges and obstacles  in your way are thoughtful and excellently designed to get you interacting with the world. I was never frustrated or confused. The level design is masterful in that sense. You are propelled further into this well crafted world where every object has meaning. Krillbite have put a lot of love and care into this experience.However, while the concept works on paper, I found Among the Sleep to be a little lacking in its narrative punch. My conclusion is that it is hamstrung by the protagonist being a toddler. Krillbite do a great job of bringing to life the world through a child's eyes. All manner of everyday objects loom large and will make you double take as you see monsters in coatracks and end tables with cloth draped over them. But you're also limited to having exposition be given by your teddy bear companion. You cannot read or talk. At times it feels as though you are being very forcibly spoon-fed the narrative, and it comes off a bit clunky. The concept works as both a fantastic creative constraint, but also a difficult barrier to overcome.I'm a great fan of suspense, interactive storytelling, and adventure. Maybe it's unfair to compare this to Frictional Games' Amnesia series and its successor SOMA - but that's precisely where this game sits. The same interaction methods, the same obstacle, narrative, obstacle, narrative beat - the same horror/suspense theming. Among the Sleep's contemporaries have hit some pretty high notes. They explore deep philosophical questions in great detail. Among the Sleep's message, which I won't spoil here, just didn't land with the same weight.I don't regret my time with Among the Sleep, but I can't recommend it over other, similar titles. If you haven't played SOMA, it'll knock your socks off. If you have and you loved it, this just won't reach the same level."
,Recommended,250620,31749331,Posted: 14 May,all,ryansett,"This game puts you in the perspective of a 2 year old child...think the old cartoon rugrats. The imagination and creativity of a 2 year old takes scenarios and situations and blows them way out of reality. The scares of this game are sure to give you goosebumps. Best played in a cool dark room with good headphones.The game starts off with your 2nd birthday and your with your mother and father being separated, she seems to have custody of you and things are a little too much for her to handle so she copes by drinking a lot. With all the hallucinations  it's likely she was kind enough to share....she probably spiked the juice... You have a stuffed animal who can speak to you and help guide you. Creepy lil teddy bear. The perspective of a child wondering a house seen through the eyes and imagination of the 2 year old. To a 2 year, old parents can be seen as monsters to avoid during rough times.  This title was very spooky at times, and often terrifying. This is a great title and I give it a definite recommend."
