,Recommended,250620,16947709,"Posted: 8 July, 2015",all,Muir,"Please note that this is an in depth review and whilst I have tried to not give any spoilers to the game, reading this review in it's entirety might give some of it away. If you do not wish for your playthrough to be spoiled at all, you may want to skip to the bottom once you've read the ""Brief Synopsis"" section.Brief Synopsis:Among the Sleepis a fairly short 1st person, on rails game. You play the part of an unnamed toddler who is accompanied by his best friend. While this game is on rails, it does allow to explore the game world quite a bit. The game is simple to play, yet provides a bit of a challenge by the way of puzzles and interactive items. The store page hashorroras one of the tags for this game. I would categorise it along the lines of being ""heart pounding inducing"". There is no blood, no guts, no real violence, but it's still enough to get the heart rate up.Long Review:*The following may contain slight spoilers. Skip to the bottom if you don't want anything about the game spoiled for you*Story:InAmong the Sleep, you play as a small toddler who wakes up in the middle of the night. Accompanied only by a teddy bear, you must brave the monster filled darkness to find the source of True Comfort - your mother.Graphics:The game is in 3D first person view and (I believe) is Oculus Rift supported (though you don't need it in order to play). The in world graphics have been beautifully rendered, with a lot of the items you find throughout the game interactable, allowing you to pick up, throw, push, and pull almost everything in the game. Well, everything that a one year old would be able to handle that is.Music/Sounds:Another huge plus for this game is its haunting music and sound effects. They're really well done, to the point where I cringed every time I accidentally broke glass objects while exploring the world.Length:Among the Sleepis not very long at all. Saying that, the plot is done so well that it doesn't need to be long. Indeed, my opinion is if the game was any longer, it would actually be to the games detriment. You don't always need a game to last for hours on end. Often, short and sweet drives the point of the story home more than long and drawn out ever could.Replayability:Unless you want to go for 100% achievements or want to speed run the game after leisurely playing it through the first time, there really isn't any replayability to this game.Overall,Among the Sleepis a short game with a really deep story. I highly recommend this game for that alone. The superb graphics and unforgetable music are just icing on cake, really."
