76561198008718046,Recommended,250620,10351946,"Posted: 4 June, 2014",all,Mr. Have A Nice Day,"'Among the Sleep' is an indie first-person horror adventure game on Steam, about the thirtieth to come out since Amnesia: The Dark Descent became wildly popular and everyone started pumping out crappy copycats like half-bred mutts at a puppy mill. Regardless of how tired I am of seeing 'of Horror' or 'Lovecraft' or 'Dark' being added on to a bunch of half♥♥♥♥♥♥♥titles, Among the Sleep caught my eye as a birthday game release and after reading the concept, decided to take a chance on it.The game's protagonist is a two-year old boy living with his single mother, and apart from thudding heartbeats and occasional toddleresque grunts of fear or exertion it's no surprise that the main character follows the Gordon Freeman camp of protagonist dialogue. This makes perfect sense, given little Gordy's age, but in order to give voice to the character's emotions and the player's observations, a birthday-gift Teddy bear takes on the Alyx Vance role as vocal sidekick, though whether he's 'magic' or just an imagined sidekick is left up to the player.It might not be immediately appealing to read that the main character is a toddler. It sounds gimmicky and hard to pull off, and I'm sure it was. But Krillbite Studios took the challenge seriously; the mechanics, story, and aesthetic all embrace this concept wholly and do it well.The gameplay matches the controls and concept; most of your challenges involve simple scavenger hunting, or moving objects around to climb on to reach other areas. This doesn't really get boring, because the game isn't very long. There are some wheel-crankings and such, but the puzzles are simple to work out and it's clear that Krillbite are more interested in seeing you enjoy the aesthetic and atmosphere than they want to stump you with a real brain-teaser. I mean for God's sake, you're a two-year-old; the puzzles aren't going to throw you for a serious loop.The environments are haphazard and nutty without being confusing or messy; the nighttime dreamscapes of an infant made playable. The art style itself isn't groundbreaking or super high-def, but they're clearly creating workable, playable, surreal environments that avoid the clutter-crap-style that some other horror indies I've played attain (cough, Anna).The triumph of Among the Sleep's style is that the environments start feeling consistently tense and foreboding because of how close and immense they feel in comparison to you. Again, they're really embracing the concept of little Gordy being a small, frightened child alone in a large, frightening world. The wooded areas feel like a 3-D rendition of Limbo with the level of character helplessness you'd expect to find while playing Slender.Among the Sleep is a horror game that offers a new twist on the gameplay and does it well from every angle. It has a pretty short playtime but also never drags on. The story ends pretty abruptly and the little details and hints are never made entirely clear, but the game ends with a pretty big emotional punch to the gut."
,Recommended,250620,10354717,"Posted: 5 June, 2014",all,H2O Delirious,I will find mommy!
