76561198001552682,Recommended,250620,10295816,"Posted: 30 May, 2014",all,Rampage,"3/5Good Music and environment, surreal and immersive, but too brief, overpriced, and simplistic.Literally Amnesia for babiesA lot of people have said the same things about this game already, so this is pretty much rehashing the public opinion. Nevertheless, I enjoyed the game. It was immersive, and had the child-like whimsy I'd expect, with a growing sense of dread and fear always lurking in the background. Even in the opening credits, when the black smoke crawls across the floor, or when the mother looks away and leaves you alone, and you start to panic in your chair, little moments like that helped seal the deal for me.The settings were interesting, pleasantly surreal and vibrant, even when they are dimly lit. However, most of the objects and things you come across are random and have no significance, aside from the scrawled drawings all over. The puzzles were fairly simple, which allows you to focus a bit more on the story. Or it would, if the story was much more than explore the place until you solve the puzzle...The monsters shocked me at first, and even throughout the first encounters I was paralyzed in my hiding spot. However, after a while when I realized they were easily avoided I had little issue and little to fear.At one point I even got caught, which sends you back to a checkpoint, and instantly reduces the terror they represent when they become little more than a funny looking obstacle.The ending wasn't a twist or a surprise if you pay attention at all to any of the sketchy stick figures, and the bottles littering the place. I was hoping for something a bit darker, but perhaps it's appropriate to have it be something so simple yet devastating... Poignant, but not very exciting.I think I enjoyed the playground level the best...Big issue is it's so brief for it's pricetag. $19.99 for something you're done with in a couple hours, with nothing in the way of replay value.  If the price were halved, it would be more reasonable, and more fitting for its content."
