76561198121313892,Recommended,250620,12100438,"Posted: 14 September, 2014",all,cortexiguy,"Assuming the role of a todder on their second birthday, players of Among the Sleep go on a dark, atmospheric journey that expertly plays on childhood fears and anxieties to create an immersive, if uneven, experience.After being put to bed by their mother, the player interacts with their new birthday present: Teddy the teddy bear. Teddy guides the player out of the bright, warm bedroom and into a dark, forbidding world. Stuck in this world away from their mother, the player must explore the dark environments and solve puzzles to recieve items which represent fond memories of their mother.The player explores the world by slowly walking through the environments or by crawling, which is much faster. The player is able to climb over obstacles and interact with many objects in the world. In dark areas, the player can hold Teddy tight, making the toddler feel more confident and lighting the way. The design is minimalistic and encourages the player to immerse themselves in the toddler's world.The environments are distorted perceptions of a normal household. The dark tone makes things appear more menacing than they would normally, adding to the tense atmosphere. In several environments, a dark presence hunts the player, forcing them to hide. The gameplay in these sections feel similar to Slender: The Arrivial but requires the player to hide, rather than run away, adding to the tension.Among the Sleep is short but still feels repetitive toward the end. The final section is satisfying enough to warrant a playthrough and the game as a whole delievers a well crafted psychological experience."
