,Recommended,250620,12142413,"Posted: 18 September, 2014",all,ID_DOOMER,"Among the Sleep is not your conventional AAA title, and as such, cannot really be judged against them. It is, however, excellent. The pacing, especially considering that this is a game that you can easily complete in one sitting, assuming your heart can take it, is absolutely spot on. The tutorial blends seemlessly with the flow of the game; while the level design is detailed and beautiful, and, while linear, doesn't feel restricting. The controls are simple, with no excessively complex button mappings to memorise, don't forget to lean around a corner or two though... The music is that perfect blend of atmospheric without being so attention grabbing that you stop feeling immersed. Lastly, the story, while simple, will definitely take you on a rollercoaster of emotion. There will be no spoilers here, but here are my four best bits of advice regarding Among the Sleep:1) Remember, all this is through the eyes of a child, let the game immerse you in such.2) Keep an eye out for the drawings scattered around, they'll not only help build the story, but may be key to your progression...3) Play it in a darkened room, headphones if you've got them (not necessary, but I played with just my speakers and succeeded in freaking myself out with the random noises in the empty flat around me).4) Get it! Play it! It's so completely worth it!Good hunting!- id_doomerFootnote: If your mouse doesn't work as a control interface, like mine didn't; it may mean that your joystick is plugged in, as Among the Sleep will default to using the joystick as an input source first. A rare situation in today's PC gaming world, I know, but toggle it off in the option menu and you'll be fine."
,Recommended,250620,12144758,"Posted: 18 September, 2014",all,Naruchin ☆,"The atmosphere of this game is great: rooms and open spaces are fully explorable and detailed, hints about the plot are scattered all over and it's interesting to reconstruct the story. The tension is build progressively, and the tutorial is surprisingly well integrated within the game. The little plot there is is ambiguous enough to leave room for interpretation, which I always like. The ending is great!What I do have an issue with is with the questionable saving system and the checkpoint placement (I was stuck after the game crashed & unable to proceed, had to restart the game over again).Also, the idea of having the player regulate the brightness of the screen is great... until you realize you can't see a thing. Don't go overboard with it :P"
