,Recommended,250620,13855847,"Posted: 5 January, 2015",all,Cthulhu's Gribbly Monocle,"Score: 8/10Price/Value: $10Time: 2 hours*Spoilers Ahead*Among the Sleep turned out to be a wonderful surprise. You play as a wee two year old toddler navigating a world which appears nightmarish to your infant eyes. Many people will be reminded immediately of the Penumbra series when it comes to world interaction (chests, drawers, opening doors, object manipulation).Artistically, this game is lovely to look at. Coats, boots and everyday objects are made out to be creatures in the dark or stylized into the creatures themselves. The baby's room is well done and being able to look down and see your tiny self fidgeting like a child might actually do in reality is a neat little thing to include. The mother looks fantastic and the lighting sets the mood for the rather dark and sad story they are telling.This is where we get into spoilers. The gist of the story is that the creatures from your nightmares are actually your mother and, from what I am guessing, either your father or some form of social services worker. As you might have guessed from that last sentence, your mother is losing you. The symbolism that is put forth in the child's drawings scattered around the level was an interesting inclusion to go along with the theme of child abuse, alcoholism and misunderstanding that children have when these things happen really sealed this up into a gem.Seeing your mother in the floor of the kitchen, your bear in one hand and wine glass in the other weeping left me cold inside at the end. Realising that the witch in the well from your children's story is your mother and her alcoholism struck a chord and is relatable I'm sure to many people growing up from all walks of life.This is easily a gem and worth it at any price.Not really a horror title as I thought it might be more-so, but actually something much deeper and more meaningful."
76561198124828411,Recommended,250620,13909195,"Posted: 9 January, 2015",all,BloodyKharma,"Ever wanted to view the world from the eyes of a baby? The world is a much more frightening place when your a 2 year old desparately trying to come to grips with the terrors around him. Even though I KNOW that in real life I'm a  grown MAN when I take the role of the main charcter whose a baby I feel truly helpless, I have nothing to help me combat the monsters that lurk in the darkness, and I know that no one is coming to rescue me. At certain points in the game I was truly scared, and my heart was racing a mile a minute as I waddled to safety beneath beds, chairs or whatever else I could hide behind. If your looking to play something unique and scary then you should certainly give this game a shot!"
