76561197983197880,Recommended,250620,12961214,"Posted: 15 November, 2014",all,Blast Hardcheese,"This is another survival/exploration horror game, but one in which you play as a two year old child. Somehow, this makes the whole thing that much more terrifying, even if the game itself isn't a pants-filler like Outlast. It's not just that you're defenseless and don't want to get eaten by some monstrosity, but you also don't want the little kid you're playing to get hurt either. It definitely adds to the fear.As others have said, the game is a bit short, although they recently added some free DLC, which helps round it out a bit. The design is interesting in that it actually feels like what a toddler might imagine based on the pieces he can put together from the world and events around him. It even reminded me of snippets that I can remember from when I was a little kid, from imaginary worlds to fragments of dreams.The mechanics are relatively simple and involve a fair amount of finding Tab A and getting it into Slot B before progressing. It's a common element in many games, and at least it isn't obstructive or overt here.The story is what got to me, though. I don't want to spoil anything, but pay attention to those crayon drawings you see littering the place and various recurring themes and objects. Some parts were fairly obvious, some were a bit of a surprise, but regardless, it was heartbreaking at points. Making the player a little kid brings out the sadness of many things.I definitely recommend picking this one up. If you're wary, grab the demo or wait for a sale. Parents playing this game might just find themselves giving their kids a big hug after playing."
