76561197970388122,Recommended,250620,17636196,"Posted: 20 August, 2015",all,burchert,"I absolutely recommend this game, it provides some unique experiences.Playing a toddler is not only a unique idea, it is actually integrated into the game world - I really felt the vulnerability of the small kid when I played the game. The toddler perpective is also the ""glue"" that brings the otherwise un-relatable story layers together.What makes the game very special is the ""mind♥♥♥♥"" aspect. The game starts with two layers of story -the ""real world"" and the phantasy world of the toddler where the main quest takes place. At the very end of the game, both layers are enriched by a background story (meta layer) which puts all events into a new - and very disturbing - perspective. To avoid spoilers I will not go into details.I cannot name another game that made me think about its story that way - and especially, in what position the game puts me as a player. Enjoying the ""main quest"" as a toddler is the obvious purpose of the game, but things get uncomfortable when it is revealed what the main quest represents.All this is delivered without being overly mysterious and confusing (compared to movies of this type) and without the usage of the ususal ""tools"" - very creepy environemtns, gore and violence - it only happens in your mind when you think through the different levels of the story.This game is actually story-driven in the best possible way, but also still relies on traditional game mechanics - which differentiates it from walking simulators.The only (mild) complain that I have is the short playtime."
