,Recommended,250620,29458716,Posted: 24 January,all,aylinaurora,"I'm not gonna lie, I only bought this game because it was supposed to be a first person ''horror'' game that puts you in the position of a toddler in a living nightmare.Personally, I wouldn't say it's a horror game, I'd rather use the word... spooky. Yes, there are a couple of jump-scares down the road, but that's it. It doesn't play with your anxierty like Outlast: Whistleblower does.When I first started Among the Sleep, I didn't like it that much, but I continued playing it anyway. It wasn't until the middle of the game (the forest part) that I started getting into it.What's brilliant about this game is that you don't know if the toddler is just having a nightmare or he's actually living it! You suddenly find yourself in a twisted reality while you're looking for your mom, who is nowhere to be seen. You don't know if something took her or fs she's still alive. Also, you have a creepy talking bear guiding you to your death. I actually didn't expect that ending, it's an interesting mature twist I didn't see coming.  It gives it a whole different meaning to the game, and makes you want to play it all over again to get all the references/hints you didn't at first (but that's just me, you might not want to play this game twice). I wanted more to the story, a more conclusive ending, but it was okay I guess.That's why I recommend this game. I love misleading storylines. It's a very short game, but it's worth it if you don't mind solving puzzles and avoiding shadowy figures. Also, the atmosphere is kind of creepy, which I love.I'll rate it 8/10 because I didn't expect the ending, and I screamed like a baby twice."
