76561198165664626,Recommended,250620,33862166,Posted: 28 July,all,Rebecca Sensecal,"This was an atmospheric game that is well worth playing. I had a few frustrations with the controls and the saving system, I played on a gaming laptop, with just a touchpad and no mouse. Mostly, the controls were okay, but there were a few places where you have to wind things and it took me a while to work out how to do that on my touchpad (for anyone else having the same trouble: hold down the left touchpad button and then draw circles on the touchpad, rather than the more expected swiping in the direction you want to wind). There were also a couple of times where I needed to throw items, but there was no linked key. I had to come out of the game and edit the controls before I could throw anything.I was also confused by the saves. Every time I picked up a drawing, it said my game was saving. And if I died, I seemed to go back to set check-points. But if I exited the game part way through a chapter, I didn't re-enter either at my most recently collected drawing or at somewhere that had been a check-point after dying. Instead, I seemed to wind up back at the start of a chapter, which was a bit frustrating. As others have mentioned, this would probably have been best played in a single gaming session, but I had to play in relatively short bursts as there are lots of swaying movements and flickering lights and it did make me feel rather nauseated at times!However, the game itself looks amazing and is genuinely creepy at times. You quickly learn to make yourself inconspicious but I may have spent rather more time hiding under bookcases than I strictly needed to. I would have been disapppointed with the amount of game that's here if I'd paid full price, but I picked it up for less than £4 and would recommend this game highly for that."
76561198354043040,Recommended,250620,34532600,Posted: 27 August,all,RelaxedGamer767,This games was good. It had awesome horror elements to it being a toddler and all. It does sometimes become a little repetitive but other than that I give it 5 stars
76561198026662084,Recommended,250620,34580336,Posted: 29 August,all,InDIGnation,"Judged solely from a gameplay perspective, Among the Sleep isn’t especially remarkable: a first-person survival horror game with simple puzzle-solving elements (even making use of a similar mouse-click interface found in Frictional titles) and somewhat simplistic monster chases. Where this quirky game really excels is the execution of its unique storyline.You’re placed in the teeny shoes of a two-year-old toddler who must search for his mother after being thrust into a series of vivid dreamscapes that all encompass some warped vision of childhood memories and fears. Everything in the world seems massive and imposing - even the coats found hanging in wardrobes bear a resemblance to domineering adults in the eyes of a frightened and confused child. This exaggerated verticality isn’t something you’ll likely consciously notice at first, but it’s a subtly effective way of making the world feel hostile and unfamiliar. The Unity-powered visuals won’t win any awards for technical prowess, but the art and sound design do an excellent job at building the atmosphere.But while the level design does a decent job at establishing the atmosphere, it does a much poorer job of giving it any significant payoff. There are only a handful of monster encounters in the course of the story, and it’s unlikely you’ll find them particularly scary if you’ve played any survival horror games before. Their behaviour is so heavily scripted and lacking in challenge that most people will find sneaking past them to be a cakewalk (In my case, I didn’t end up dying once). There is an argument to be had that making a horror game too difficult can result in something more frustrating than scary. At the same time though, when there’s no tangible threat to the player during these moments, it’s hard for me to really take the monster chases seriously - particularly when I once ran the wrong way and was able to walk right past one without it seeming to notice.The story however, is something I haven’t seen done before in a video game -the portrayal of an abusive relationship as seen through the eyes of a young child. You eventually learn that the environments aren’t merely spooky dreamscapes, but represent the fears and anxieties of this small lad’s mind as he struggles to comprehend the emotional torment going on around him. Among the Sleep pulls this off surprisingly well without having to resort to explicit images or gratuitous violence - instead, we’re able to understand this childhood fear through symbolism and subtle environmental cues. It’s a shame that the conclusion feels rather abrupt and ends on a slightly rushed note, but the game’s short three-hour length at least means that the story never feels padded or overstretched.Taken as a whole, Among the Sleep is a somewhat variable survival horror experience - it’s gameplay, while intuitive enough, doesn’t really do enough to connect the player the the narrative itself, which I suspect might lead some people to label the game as little more than a walking simulator. Despite this, the story Krillbite has conjured up, while not always coherent, is unique and interesting.TL:DR: If you’re looking for a substantial gameplay experience, then you might be better off with one of Among the Sleep’s many horror contemporaries. If you’re looking for something a little special, then this is still worth picking up on the cheap."
,Recommended,250620,34523268,Posted: 27 August,all,khal froyo,"Short game and simple puzzles, however very compelling story and does well to play on your own fears, rather than relying on jump scares. Certainly worth the price of admission, will be interested to see what comes next!"
76561198074462780,Recommended,250620,34508428,Posted: 26 August,all,EloquentElephant,"The horror aspect of this game does not come from cheap jumpscares or scary music, but the entire atmosphere of the game is one of tension. Whether you're running from a scary tree lady, hiding under shelves and desks, or simply walking through the house at night passing by empty bottles of alcohol and hearing your mother crying in the background. The story can be hard to catch, but if you're looking for it, it's an incredibly well told one.  I would definitely recommend this game. It's a little short, but the story is so definitely worth it."
